description: Large original V8, spacious cabin, and darning angular styling â€“ what was once the top luxury vehicle for the '60s is now a vintage cruiser with all the right flair.  So when this 1969 Cadillac Eldorado is also so affordable, it's time to take notice.

The design lines of the sixth generation Eldorado are ones of legend.  It's a true statement of personal luxury with flowing details.  The extra long hood starts with a sharp middle point and  begins a crease line that runs uninterrupted to the doors and emphasizes the sporty kick-up on the rear quarter panels.  And the super-slick rear end was there to let you know the excess of the tailfin era was over, but this Cadillac still knew how to pay homage to its history.  Also, while you're checking out the rear, take a look at the bumper.  That chrome king is integrated into the design better than you can even get on a modern Cadillac.  And if its brightwork you like, the front bumper shines just as brilliantly.  You can see all of these details so well because of the level of care that has gone into this Caddy.  The sheetmetal looks amazing, and the doors still shut with authority.  And on top of this straight body is the original shade of Astral Blue that has the kind of gloss to highlight every crease so this Eldorado looks like a finely pressed suit.  The pristine blue vinyl top not only gives this coupe a very European color scheme, but also it gives you a preview of the interior.

Inside, you'll love how everything from the wood paneling on the door to the plushness of the carpets have defied the decades.  The driver's seat has been worn in a bit, but quite frankly, you probably wish you were this complete as you approach nearly half a century on this earth.  Plus, you get the kind of luxury that made these Cadillacs so special in 1969, and the kind of options that you would expect in a brand new car today.  This includes power seats, power windows, power locks, tilt steering wheel, rear defogger, the original AM/FM stereo, and provisions for automatic climate control. You sit behind the original Caddy three-spoke steering wheel and gaze at a clear gauge package.  And all the controls are centered around you, because this is built to be a personal luxury machine.  But on those days when you want to share the comfort with family and friends, the flat floor of the Eldorado means it really does offer relaxed seating for up to six total.

The 472 cubic-inch V8 fills the engine bay, because this was the era when Cadillac was a true master at offering big motors with big power.  And more than just being the original numbers-matching V8, you can really tell there has been proper care and maintenance over the years thanks to items like the fresh hoses and belts.  Plus, there has been a great eye to preservation as noted by all the factory decals still present under the hood. description: For sale in our Denver showroom is a time capsule of a car, a 1969 Cadillac DeVille convertible in showroom condition. After being stored for 25 years, this beauty was resurrected. In 2011 it was fully serviced, painted, new top, new tires, battery, and more. Driving this land yacht with the top down is surely a great way to clear your mind or take a memorable cruise to see the sights. It drives nearly like it did new, it's amazing! Under the hood is a 472 CID V8 engine backed by a smooth shifting automatic transmission. This Caddy is fully loaded with character as well as options. options include: AC, AM/FM radio, automatic convertible top, cruise control, hub caps, power brakes, power steering, power seats, power windows, tilt wheel, seat belts, leather interior, and white wall radial tires. In 1969 DeVille was restyled in the Eldorado image. An Eldorado-like front fender treatment evolved and helped to emphasize a stronger horizontal design line. Rear quarters were extended to give the car a longer look. There was an all new grille with dual horizontal headlamps positioned in the outboard step-down areas of the grille. The hood was again extended, a total of 2.5 inches to add the impression of extra length. The roofline was squarer and the rear deck and bumper more sculptured. A new ventilation system eliminated the need for vent windows, which provided a longer sleeker look and improved visibility. The looks of this Caddy are as strong as the 472 V8 powering it forward. Drop the top and enjoy the sun on your shoulders. If you get hot, flip the AC on high. To view this car in greater detail, including an HD video and 100+ HD pictures visit www.gatewayclassiccars.com or visit our Denver showroom. Call 303-872-4722 for more information.

description: Gateway Classic Cars of Philadelphia welcomes this classy blue land yacht, a 1976 Cadillac Eldorado, to its showroom in West Deptford, NJ.  This year marked the bicentennial as well as an end to inflation that had affected markets world-wide.  Plentiful gasoline encouraged car sales suggesting whatever lessons that were learned from the Oil Embargo of 1973 were quickly forgotten.  Americans were ready to buy and buy big in that they flocked to the larger sized vehicles.  Such is the case with this beautiful 1976 Eldorado that was and continues to be a popular model to this day. Powered by the original numbers matching, rebuilt 500 CID fuel injected V8 rated at 215 horsepower, this boat is ready to set sail!  Those familiar with the ride on these longer cars know exactly what weÃ¢??re talking about when we say the car Ã¢??floatsÃ¢?Â down the highway.  A smooth shifting three-speed automatic allows for effortless driving and a truly relaxed riding experience.  Coated in a handsome steel blue paint with white pinstripes, this Cadillac features a fully-functioning automatic top!  The last Eldorado convertibles went on sale in 1976, at least until ragtops were revived in the 1980s. Customers were quick to buy these classy convertibles and to find one in good driving condition in a real treat!  Step inside a light blue leather interior and allow yourself to relax and enjoy the drive. Place your hands on the classy steering wheel emblazoned with the familiar Cadillac emblem!  Imagine yourself with the top down and listening to the radio while youÃ¢??re cruising this summer.  You are sure to have eyes on you and this fine automobile.  Additional features include Cruise Control, Tilt Wheel, Power Locks, Power Seats, Power Steering, Airbags, Remote Keyless Entry, Anti-Theft System and White Wall Tires.To view this 1976 Cadillac Eldorado in greater detail, including HD pictures and an HD video, visit www.GatewayClassicCars.com or our Philadelphia showroom located in West Deptford, NJ. Evolve Motors & Chicago Car Club are pleased to present this 1976 Cadillac Sedan deVille!

At just shy of 20ft in length and over 5100lbs in weight, this ‘76 Sedan deVille is one big, beautiful piece of automotive history. This car is a very well-preserved example of Cadillac’s final pillar-less hardtop sedan, from a time that luxury and comfort were paramount. This car is a real dream boat, it floats down the road in a manner that can only be described as effortless. The cabin is dead silent at speed and the seats are so comfortable that a full day of highway cruising doesn’t sound even the least bit daunting.

This ‘76 Sedan deVille has covered just 65,680 miles over the course of its 42 year life. Considering the state of it’s original Firethorn Metallic paint and the matching Firethorn interior, the car has been well taken care of throughout those 42 years.
Exterior:

First off, paint. Firethorn metallic is a lovely color. While it’s considered red, it’s really much more of a coral. Paint is original, as confirmed with an elcometer, and has a great metallic sparkle to it under direct light. The paint shows very well. There are a handful of small chips scattered about the car, with by far the most significant chipping being on the driver’s side of the trunk lid (see photo). White pinstripes are without cracks or wear, and contrast extremely well against the metallic coral paint. Chrome is excellent throughout, and really completes the look of this big sedan. There is no oxidation or damage on the chrome at all; it shines nice and bright with a mirror-like finish. Landau hardtop is in pristine condition, with absolutely no scratches, scrapes, or damage. There are a few small door-dings on the car, with two light dings on the trunk lid and another on the passenger rear quarter. There is some minor bubbling beginning to form under the paint at the lowest points of the rear skirts (see photos). All doors close without any fuss. Glass is clear and crack and scratch-free throughout.
Interior:

The interior of the car presents extremely well. Phenomenally comfortable Firethorn cloth seats with leather bolsters are in great shape, with no tears or stains. Seats are powered, as are windows and mirrors. Carpets are also stain and tear free both front and rear. The car will come with its original Firethorn floormats, which are in nice shape. Headliner is tight. All powered systems are functional – dash lights, cruise control, heat, seat adjustments, radio, and gauges. Air conditioning blows, but is on R12 refrigerant and is not cold. All lights are functional both inside and out. Odometer is functional and currently reads 65,680 miles.
Under the Hood / Underbody:

This Sedan deVille retains its original 500cid 8.2L V8. The car runs and drives very, very well. Starts right up without fault, idles cool and steady, and tracks nice and straight down the road. Brakes feel very good, with no hooking in either direction. The car has no tendencies or noises of concern; it eats up speedbumps and potholes quietly and smoothly. Underneath, the car is in nice shape. There is no rust of any structural concern. Frame rails and rockers are solid. The only spot of rust is at the forward bottom corner of the driver’s side rear skirt, which we’ve provided a photo of.
